[[Image:Floodforms library.jpg|thumb|250px|right|''Halo''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Master Chief (Halo)|Master Chief]] encounters various flood forms on Installation 04.]]
The '''Flood''' is a fictional [[extraterrestrial life|alien]] [[parasite|parasitic]] life form in the ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'' video game series. They are introduced in ''[[Halo: Combat Evolved]]'' as a secondary enemy to the game's protagonist, [[Master Chief (Halo)|Master Chief]], and return in ''[[Halo 2]]''. They are depicted as highly [[virulent]] and deadly, and with the ability to quickly incapacitate and infect their victims. The Flood mutate their hosts into several different forms to serve different purposes. All of these forms have an attraction to any lifeform of sufficient mass to accommodate them and will try to attack or infect any potential host they encounter. 

The Flood make their first appearance in ''Halo: Combat Evolved''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s sixth level, "343 Guilty Spark."<!-- The Flood is not a level, it's a chapter in 343 GS --> After reaching [[Halo (megastructure)|Halo]]'s control room in the previous mission, Master Chief is sent by the AI [[Cortana]] to try and stop [[List of Halo series characters#Captain Jacob Keyes|Captain Jacob Keyes]] and his [[United Nations Space Command|UNSC]] Marines from reaching a weapons cache they believed was hidden in a [[Forerunner (Halo)|Forerunner]] structure by a swamp. In reality, the cache is false intelligence; instead of finding weapons, Keyes finds that a sizable population of Flood has been released from [[stasis]] by the [[Covenant (Halo)|Covenant]]. The Flood quickly escape containment and spread across the ringworld, threatening not only Humanity and the Covenant, but also the entire galaxy if they escape.

==Overview==
===Life cycle===
In the game, the [[biological life cycle|life cycle]] of the Flood begins at the Infection form stage, as a small, frail, creature. These creatures leap upon a potential host and attempt to drive in three barbed tentacles. Small spores that some Flood release are also used to either infect or incapacitate potential hosts, as the character [[343 Guilty Spark]] explains during the level "The Library" in ''Halo: Combat Evolved''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://halosm.bungie.org/story/level_transcripts/lv07_library.html|title= ''Halo'' Story Page Level Transcripts|work=halo.bungie.org|accessdate=Mar 10|accessyear=2006}}</ref> The infection form burrows into the host, who quickly loses motor functions and control, and begins mutating the host body.<ref>{{cite book |last= Dietz|first= William|title=[[Halo: The Flood]]|year= 2003|publisher= Ballantine Books|location=New York |isbn=0-345-45921-0 |pages=140}}</ref> If the host is of a suitable size, the infection form mutates the host into a Combat form.<ref name=h295>{{cite book |author= Piggyback||title=''Halo 2: The Official Strategy Guide: The Flood]''|year= 2004|publisher= Piggyback Interactive Ltd.|location=United States |isbn=0-7615-4473-9|pages=95}}</ref> If the host is not of sufficient size, or is not useful in battle, the next stage of mutation occurs. The upper body swells and incubates new Infection forms, creating a Carrier form. When the Carrier Form detects a suitable host in their proximity, they explode, releasing the Infection forms inside of them to continue the cycle.<ref name=h295 />

===Origins===
{{seealso|Forerunners (Halo)}}
The origins of the Flood have never been fully explained by ''Halo'' media. In ''Halo: Combat Evolved'' the player learns that the ring they are playing on, [[Halo (megastructure)#Installation 04|Halo]], was built by the [[Forerunners (Halo)|Forerunners]] to contain the Flood, as well as being a weapon of last resort if the Flood were to escape.<ref>'''343 Guilty Spark''': The installation was specifically built to study and contain the Flood. Their survival as a race was dependent upon it. I am grateful to see that some of them survived to reproduce. - {{cite video game
