===Game Development===
The Flood were added later in the game development stage of ''Halo: Combat Evolved'', after the game had made its jump from the [[Apple Macintosh|Macintosh]] platform and Bungie was bought by [[Microsoft]]. At one point, the ringworld ''Halo'' featured dinosaur-like terrestrial creatures, but due to gameplay constraints, these were dropped. An additional consideration was that Bungie felt the presence of other native species would dilute the impact and surprise of the Flood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bungie.net/News/TopStory.aspx?story=prexboxhistory040904 |title=One Million Years B.X. |author=Bungie|date=2006-02-10 |work=bungie.net|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20060210224125/http://www.bungie.net/News/TopStory.aspx?story=prexboxhistory040904 |archivedate=2006-02-10 }}</ref>

==Flood forms==
===Infection forms=== 
[[Image:Flood3.jpg|thumb|150px|Infection form]]
The first Flood form encountered by the player during ''Halo'', infection forms are small creatures which use tentacles for mobility and infection, and are the base forms of Flood. They appear to have their own defined biological framework, as in the games they are seen without a host and do not appear to need one to survive. Individually they are weak and fragile; in the game they usually appear in large swarms. The infection forms will seek out any sentient life of sufficient [[Biomass (ecology)|bio-mass]] and [[calcium]] deposits to sustain itself, and proceed to attempt to use the creature as a host, by burrowing into the thoracic cavity, tapping into the spinal/nervous system, suppressing the host's consciousness, and releasing spores which cause the host to mutate. [[343 Guilty Spark]] mentions these "spores" during ''Halo: Combat Evolved''.<ref>'''343 Guilty Spark:''' You can see how the body's been transformed by the genetic restructuring of the Flood infection. The small creatures carry spores that cause a host to mutate. The mutated host then produces spores that can pass the Flood to others. - {{cite video game
| title = [[Halo: Combat Evolved]]
| developer = Bungie Studios
| publisher = Microsoft
| date = 2001
| platform =
| version = 
| level = The Library
| language = English
| isolang = 
| quote = 
}}</ref> The host then begins to mutate into other forms.

In the ''Halo'' fiction, infection forms are seen to be unable to breach energy shields- those of the Master Chief's [[MJOLNIR]] armor, for instance, or the shields of [[Covenant Elite]]s. However non-shielded enemies and allies are extremely vulnerable to attack; a regular Marine or Grunt's personnel armor can be pierced by the Infection form's tentacles.<ref>{{cite book |last= Dietz|first= William|title=[[Halo: The Flood]]|year= 2003|publisher= Ballantine Books|location=New York |isbn=0-345-45921-0 |pages=282}}</ref>

===Combat forms===
<!-- [[Image:Flood Human.jpg|thumb|150px|Human Combat form]] -->
If the host is strong or deemed "useful" by the parasitic infection form, it will be converted into a warrior or worker form, used in both defensive and offensive situations. In the game, the combat forms were mainly infected Marines and Covenant Elites. As the Flood are seen to utilize the memories and knowledge of their hosts,<ref>{{cite book |last= Hammack|first= Lee|title=''[[Halo graphic novel#The Last Voyage of the Infinite Succor|The Last Voyage of the Infinite Succor]]''|year= 2006|publisher= Marvel Comics|location=United States |isbn=0785123725|pages=25}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Dietz|first= William|title=[[Halo: The Flood]]|year= 2003|publisher= Ballantine Books|location=New York |isbn=0-345-45921-0 |pages=192}}</ref> they can repair or utilize weapons or machinery their hosts could use. These warrior or combat forms are extremely strong and agile, and are seen to be able to jump to extreme distances and heights, and attack enemies with whip-like tentacles. While damage to the host's head and limbs does not give the Combat form pause, eliminating the infection form embedded within the host's chest will disable the combat form. Combat forms ignore any threat to themselves and those fighting alongside them and will often kill themselves to kill an opponent.<ref name=h296>{{cite book |author= Piggyback||title=''Halo 2: The Official Strategy Guide: Combat Forms''|year= 2004|publisher= Piggyback Interactive Ltd.|location=United States |isbn=0-7615-4473-9|pages=96}}</ref>

===Carrier forms===
[[Image:Carrier Flood.jpg|thumb|150px|Carrier Form]]
The third stage of the Flood cycle. Carriers grow large sacs which contain several infection forms. When a carrier is in close proximity to any number of suitable hosts or is sufficiently damaged, it triggers a biochemical reaction which causes the sacs to explode and release the infection forms in order to infect more hosts. Carrier forms cannot physically attack; however, the explosion of a carrier form is roughly equivalent to a grenade detonation, killing any Flood or Covenant within the blast radius.<ref name=h276>{{cite book |author= Piggyback||title=''Halo 2: The Official Strategy Guide: Carrier Forms''|year= 2004|publisher= Piggyback Interactive Ltd.|location=United States |isbn=0-7615-4473-9|pages=76}}</ref> Loose [[grenades]] are also set off by a carrier form's explosion. If carrier forms are hurled into the air by another's explosion, they will explode upon landing. They are thought also to be made after a combat form serves its purpose. The combat form will then convert itself into a carrier form.<ref name=h276 />

===Brain forms===
[[Image:Brainform Flood.jpg|thumb|150px|Captain Keyes, mutated into a Brain Form]]
Brain forms are large, spongy creatures resembling a large bag of flesh with tentacles. They are seen used in ''Halo: The Flood'' to collect important data, such as codes, planet locations, and information about the species that the Flood can infect. In ''Halo'', [[Captain Jacob Keyes]] was subjected to an 'interrogation' of sorts by one of these forms before finally being completely assimilated. The Brain Form was then later damaged by the Master Chief during the level "Keyes".<ref>'''Cortana:''' No human life signs detected. The Captain... he's one of ''them!'' - {{cite video game
| title = [[Halo: Combat Evolved]]
| developer = Bungie Studios
| publisher = Microsoft
| date = 2001
| platform =
| version = 
| level = Keyes
| language = English
| isolang = 
| quote = 
}}</ref>

Over time, the Brain Form strips memories and information from its victims. It appears that the Brain Form has some sort of intelligence, as it was able to use Keyes' own memories against him, in an effort to learn more about Earth.<ref name=tf200/> However, Keyes is able to resist giving the Flood information regarding the location of Earth when he realizes that the Flood cannot strip away information that he could draw from his neural implants, such as his name, rank, serial number, and the name of the ship that he commanded. Thus by "feeding" the Flood that information, he could continue to access it and withhold everything else.<ref name=tf200>{{cite book |last= Dietz|first= William|title=[[Halo: The Flood]]|year= 2003|publisher= Ballantine Books|location=New York |isbn=0-345-45921-0 |pages=200}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Dietz|first= William|title=[[Halo: The Flood]]|year= 2003|publisher= Ballantine Books|location=New York |isbn=0-345-45921-0 |pages=225}}</ref>

===Command forms===
The command forms, due to their limited exposure in the ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'' trilogy, are not well understood. Their purpose is not exactly known. [[Gravemind]] from ''Halo 2'' is a command form over either all Flood or those on Installation 05 ([[Delta Halo]]). When the Flood invaded a Covenant supply ship in the ''[[Halo Graphic Novel]]'' story ''The Last Voyage of the Infinite Succor'' they used corpses and dead biomatter to feed what appeared to be a much smaller, developing command form, which the Prophet Legate assumed to be a sort of central brain controlling the infestation.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hammack|first= Lee|title=[[Halo Graphic Novel#The Last Voyage of the Infinite Succor|The Last Voyage of the Infinite Succor]]|year= 2006|publisher= Marvel Comics|location=United States |isbn=0785123725|pages=10}}</ref>

==Flood details==
It appears that the Flood can infect recently dead lifeforms, as the [[Hierarchs (Halo)#High Prophet of Regret|Prophet of Regret]] is assimilated by [[Gravemind]] shortly after being assassinated by the Master Chief in ''[[Halo 2]]''. However, one of the Marines in ''Halo: Combat Evolved'' evades the Flood by "playing dead".<ref>'''Marine:''' Play dead! That's what I did... played dead. They took the live ones... - {{cite video game
| title = [[Halo: Combat Evolved]]
| developer = Bungie Studios
| publisher = Microsoft
| date = 2001
| platform =
| version = 
| level = 343 Guilty Spark
| language = English
| isolang = 
| quote = 
}}</ref>It can also be noted that if the nervous system is abnormal the Flood cannot infect them either. Sgt. Avery Johnson is a prime example of this, due to having a condition known as "Boren's Syndrome," a condition that "scrambles" his nervous system and makes it impossible for the Flood to take over his body. Once the initial infection has already occurred and been completed, a new Infection form can quickly take control of a Combat form, even if the previous infection form has been incapacitated.<ref name=h296/> The Flood have also been noted to gather corpses for use in the construction of new Flood forms,<ref>'''Cortana:''' Look, in the corners... They're gathering bodies... - {{cite video game
| title = [[Halo: Combat Evolved]]
| developer = Bungie Studios
| publisher = Microsoft
| date = 2001
| platform =
| version = 
| level = Keyes
| language = English
| isolang = 
| quote = 
}}</ref> in both ''[[Halo: Combat Evolved]]'' and ''The Last Voyage of the Infinite Succor''.

Most Flood on [[Alpha Halo|Installation 04]] were destroyed due to detonation of the ''[[Pillar of Autumn]]'''s engines in ''Halo: Combat Evolved'', but in ''Halo 2'' the Flood on [[Delta Halo|Installation 05]] were similarly released. In ''Halo 2'', the Flood on [[Delta Halo]] are led by the command form [[Gravemind#The Gravemind|Gravemind]], a massive creature that dwells beneath Delta Halo's Library and takes over [[High Charity]]. In ''[[Halo: Ghosts of Onyx]]'', Flood are trying to escape Halo, but are currently being destroyed by Covenant forces aware of the danger they present if they were to escape.<ref>{{cite book |last= Nylund|first= Eric|title=[[Halo: Ghosts of Onyx]]|year= 2006|publisher= Tom Doherty Associates|location=New York |isbn=0-765-31568-8 |pages=32}}</ref>

